    {
      "id": "fd7a6ffdfb501cdbb62edd84dfea4ae6ded9590e",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2022-08-09 22:02:37.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\n> > For the \"num\" is it a unique number or something related to the hardware, like the hardware address of IB.\n >\n > It is the lower 20 bits of the MAC address of the interface.\n\nThis is going to make it somewhat cumbersome to configure the servers?  Having NIDs that are essentially random 7-digit numbers, unless you are setting a soft MAC address as part of the cluster configuration so that they are \"friendly\" numbers (e.g. == node number).",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
    {
      "id": "a5e21fc7b878623f063f367578336c85a910bf59",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 148,
        "name": "Chris Horn",
        "email": "chris.horn@hpe.com",
        "username": "hornc"
      },
      "date": "2022-08-10 15:36:20.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\n> > > For the \"num\" is it a unique number or something related to the\n > hardware, like the hardware address of IB.\n > >\n > > It is the lower 20 bits of the MAC address of the interface.\n > \n > This is going to make it somewhat cumbersome to configure the\n > servers?  Having NIDs that are essentially random 7-digit numbers,\n > unless you are setting a soft MAC address as part of the cluster\n > configuration so that they are \"friendly\" numbers (e.g. == node\n > number).\n\nThere are indeed some administrative and serviceability challenges with these nid numbers. We're looking at supporting IPv4 based NIDs with kfilnd in the future.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    }
  ],
